I love doing stuff like that, although I work in tourism my actual profession or degree is caretaker

I‚Äôve never been to Bali but it is on my bucket list, I was actually looking to come to Jakarta after the summer season. The only thing is I like to go to countries where I know people as I prefer to learn how local people live, to understand their culture, learn the language,‚Ä¶.

I can do that because I‚Äôm working abroad. I‚Äôm now in Crete, Greece. I arrived in April and I stay untill End of October. Before Crete I was in Gran Canaria, Spain. Before Spain I was in Sal, Cape Verde. Before Cape Verde I worked in The Gambia, Africa,‚Ä¶. So I always help the communities in the country in work in

My friends always come to visit me wherever I‚Äôm. I have friends coming over next week, friends came to visit me in Spain, Africa even in Mexico when I worked there . My friends are always welcome to come and stay with me wherever I‚Äôm
Greece is very nice, one of my favourite destinations
Beautiful beaches and mountains, lovely food and amazing people
Crete sounds incredible! The way you immerse yourself in local communities is so inspiring üòä What's been your favorite cultural tradition you've learned while working abroad?

Sounds maybe strange but when I worked in Mexico I celebrated the day of the dead. In Belgium, Europe that is a sad day but in Mexico they celebrate the dead. The Mexican go to the grave of their loved ones and they drink and remember their loved ones in a good way, a happy way not a depressing way like we do in Belgium.

Besides that I learned over the years that it doesn‚Äôt matter where you come from or what you do, material stuff or what you own doesn‚Äôt make you happy, the actions you do in life make you happy. You can be rich but eventually when you pass away you can‚Äôt take you house or fancy car with you, what you can with you is your memories. On the end of my life I want to pass away peacefully and happy, I want to be able to say I have no regrets. Traditions are amazing, well some are good and some are bad but on the end of the day it isn‚Äôt about traditions but what you believe in. You are the only person that has a grin on your life, you have to make the decision for yourself. I believe in karma, you do good for people, people will do good for you! Happiness is only a smile away!
What is your favourite tradition ?
Well, if you ever want to come my house is open for you

message: What do you want to know about me Kenny, just ask üòÉ
What do you want to tell me?
How old are you? What do you study? Do you have siblings? What is your plan in the future? Do you want a family? Do you like traveling? What do you like for food?‚Ä¶. So many questions

I am 24. I study Accounting. I do have 2 younger sisters and one younger brother. Ideally I would be a housewife, but I also would enjoy working a part time job, something meaningful a couple days a week. Of course I want a family. I love traveling, eventho I haven't seen much, the little I was able to travel, I really enjoyed it, so war I only traveled inside my country. I mostly enjoy Indonesian food and I have a special love for spicy food. Now its your turn üòÉ

I‚Äôm 45 and I‚Äôm a team manager in one of the biggest tour operators in Europe. I work and live now in Greece but before I worked and lived in Spain, Cape Verde, The Gambia, Bulgaria, Mexico, Ireland,‚Ä¶ From degree I‚Äôm actually a care taker. I worked before with kids who had autism and are blind, I worked aswell in an asylum centre for refugees, I works with young adults with Down syndrome. I love traveling and my biggest dream in life is to have a family. Unfortunately I haven‚Äôt been blessed with a family which is my biggest fear in life! I love Italian food but also Greek or Mexican food.

Wow Kenny, you've really lived everywhere! Greece, Spain, Cape Verde, Mexico - I'm honestly a bit jealous of all the places you've experienced üòÖ Your care work sounds really meaningful too, especially working with kids with autism and in asylum centers. That takes a really good heart. It's cool that we both love travel and want families someday. The age difference is definitely there but seems like we're after similar things in life. What has been your favorite place to live in? üòä

Yes, I have been blessed with an amazing life so far. Living in all these places, learning their culture and language made me realise that in life material things don‚Äôt matter. Love and friendship is so important, surround yourself with good people. Thank you, I didn‚Äôt do it to get recognition but I did do it out of the good of my heart. Age is a number, the important thing how you feel for each other and how you feel when you are together, what you willing to do for each other. Favourite place? So difficult to say as I loved being in every place I went to. Going somewhere is not about the place but about the people you meet. My favourite place is where I feel loved
Where do you want to go? Do you think the age difference matters?

I'd love to visit Greece someday, especially after hearing about your experiences living there! The beaches and culture seem amazing. As for the age difference, I don't think it matters as much as the connection between two people. What matters is how we support and understand each other. You're right that it's about how you feel together. Have you dated someone with a similar age gap before? How did that go?

You are welcome to come, as I said before my door is open for you ‚ò∫Ô∏è Yes, I did. When I was 43 I dated someone of 22. That was amazing but it ended as her parents didn‚Äôt agree, she was Muslim. I did t had a problem with it but her parents did. We had an amazing time

Hi Kenny, I am very busy at the moment. I have a lot to take care of. Also, my mother had a little accident so that I have to take over some of her duties.
